[[File:Erik Laykin 2008.jpg|thumb|Erik Laykin in 2008]]
'''Erik Laykin''' (born 1964, Los Angeles, California) is a [[computer forensics]] expert and cyber-crime investigator.

== Overview ==
Erik Laykin was a past President and Pacific Rim Director of the L.A. FBI [[Infragard]] program as well as Chairman of the Advisory Board of the [[EC-Council]] (Electronic Commerce Council).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eccouncil.org/about_us/governance/honorary_council.aspx |title=Honorary Council |work=eccouncil.org |accessdate=14 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429194609/http://www.eccouncil.org/about_us/governance/honorary_council.aspx |archivedate=29 April 2013 |df= }}</ref> Laykin has served as an expert witness in court in technology investigations.
{{Prose|section|date=August 2011}}
Co-founder of Online Security, Inc. with Charlie Balot in mid-1990s.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}
Established initial computer forensic capabilities on behalf of American investigative agencies [[Kroll| Kroll Inc.]], [[Investigative Group International]] and Pinkerton Investigations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esecurityplanet.com/prodser/article.php/2199301/Pinkerton-CA-Combine-to-Package-Security-Services.htm |title=Latest News about Internet Security - eSecurity Planet |work=esecurityplanet.com |accessdate=14 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311103642/http://www.esecurityplanet.com/prodser/article.php/2199301/Pinkerton-CA-Combine-to-Package-Security-Services.htm |archivedate=March 11, 2012 }}</ref> Established first commercial computer forensic labs in Los Angeles, Chicago and Hong Kong <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnetasia.com/online-labs-looking-to-establish-hong-kong-office-13019768.htm |title=Latest Topics |work=ZDNet |accessdate=14 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329034329/http://www.zdnetasia.com/online-labs-looking-to-establish-hong-kong-office-13019768.htm |archivedate=March 29, 2012 }}</ref> catering to the legal and corporate community.

Director of [[Navigant Consulting]] Inc. (NYSE:NCI)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050207005650/en/Navigant-Consulting-Adds-Computer-Forensics-Specialized-Technology|title=Navigant Consulting Adds Computer Forensics and Specialized Technology Experts to Discovery Services Practice - Business Wire|publisher=}}</ref> from 2004 - 2008 where he established the Information Technology Investigations Practice and worked with noted industry leaders Jennifer Baker and James Gordon.

Managing Director of [[Duff & Phelps]], LLC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duffandphelps.com/expertise/our_team/Pages/bio.aspx?ID=183&list=People|title=Services|work=duffandphelps.com|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> as of 2008 where he is the co-practice chair of the Global Electronic Discovery and Investigations practice. Led the Data Forensics and eDiscovery Investigative team (2009–2010) on behalf of the court-appointed [[Lehman Brothers]] [[Lehman bankruptcy|bankruptcy]] examiner, Anton Valukis,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duffandphelps.com/Pages/newsDetail.aspx?list=News&ID=266&DisplayLang=us |title=Unknown Server Error |work=duffandphelps.com |accessdate=14 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901190754/http://www.duffandphelps.com/Pages/newsDetail.aspx?list=News&ID=266&DisplayLang=us |archivedate=September 1, 2014 }}</ref> the chairman of [[Jenner & Block]], whose extensive [[Report of Anton R. Valukas|report]] brought to light Lehman Brothers usage of [[Repo 105]].

Laykin was appointed by California Insurance Commissioner and Gubernatorial Candidate Steve Poizner to the California Department of Insurance Anti-Fraud Task Force where he chaired the technology committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insurance.ca.gov/0400-news/0100-press-releases/0060-2007/release047-07.cfm |title=Document Not Found |work=ca.gov |accessdate=14 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930000347/http://www.insurance.ca.gov/0400-news/0100-press-releases/0060-2007/release047-07.cfm |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref>  Laykin was featured in the 2010 History Channel - [[A&E Network]] series ''Partners in Crime'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://citvasia.com/partnersincrime.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 8, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207132928/http://citvasia.com/partnersincrime.aspx |archivedate=February 7, 2011 }}</ref> episode "Control-Alt-Delete", which highlighted a number of his high tech investigations in Asia. The program was syndicated by the [[Crime & Investigation Network (South East Asia)]] throughout Asia. Laykin is featured in the 2013 Smithsonian Channel series "''Forensic Firsts''" and "''Catching Criminals''" which chronicles a variety of investigations which utilize the forensic sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianchannel.com/site/sn/show.do?series=1003122|title=Smithsonian Channel: Home|publisher=}}</ref> Who's Who Legal selected Laykin as one of 50 top global Digital Forensic Experts in 2014,2015 and 2016 calling him:  "the authority on e-discovery and digital forensics".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whoswholegal.com/profiles/54298/0/laykin/erik-laykin/|title=Who's Who Legal}}</ref>

Laykin is a contributing author of "''The Life and Death of a DotCom in China''" published by Asia Law & Practice in 2000.  
Laykin's book "''Investigative Computer Forensics''" was published by John Wiley & Sons in 2013. {{ISBN|978-0-470-93240-7}}

