|title     = 
|quote     = "COUM enable all kinds of people to discover their abilities to express ideas through different media. COUM believe that you don't NEED special training to produce and/or enjoy, worthwhile, significant and unique works. COUM demonstrate that there are NO boundaries in any form. It has NOT all been done before, and that which has can still bear valid re-interpretation. Thee [sic] possibilities remain endless."
|salign    = right
|source    = COUM Manifesto, 1974.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.11}} }}

In January 1974, COUM returned their attention to music, collaborating with the Canadian artist [[Clive Robertson (artist)|Clive Robertson]] to produce ''Marcel Duchamp's Next Work'', which they premiered at an arts festival in the [[Zwaarte Zaal]] in [[Ghent]], Belgium.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.5}} COUM's next major work was ''Couming of Age'', performed in March 1974 at the [[Oval House]] in [[Kennington]], [[South London]].{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.9}} After the show, they were approached by an audience member, [[Peter Christopherson]], who shared many of their interests; P-Orridge and Tutti nicknamed him "Sleazy" because of his particular interest in the sexual aspects of COUM's work.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.9}} He began to aid them using his skills as a photographer and graphic designer, and would first perform with them in their March 1975 work ''Couming of Youth''.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.10}} In May 1974, COUM issued a manifesto published on an [[A3 paper|A3]] double-sided sheet titled ''Decoumpositions and Events''.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=4.10&ndash;4.11}}

In April 1974 the [[Arts Council of Great Britain]] gave COUM the first half of a £1,500 grant.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.11}} The money stabilised the group, which now included P-Orridge and Tutti as directors, John Gunni Busck as technical director, and Lelli Maull as musical director.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.11}} During that year, they made use of various artist-run venues in London, most notably the Art Meeting Place (AMP) in [[Covent Garden]], where they regularly performed during 1974.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.12}} A number of these works entailed P-Orridge and Tutti exploring the gender balance, including concepts of gender confusion.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=4.13&ndash;4.15}} In one performance at the AWB, which was titled ''Filth'', P-Orridge and Tutti performed sexual acts using a double-ended [[dildo]].{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.12}} COUM were frustrated with the restrictions imposed on them by the Arts Council as a prerequisite for receiving funding; rather than performing at Council-accredited venues, they wanted to perform more spontaneously.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.18}} In August 1974 they carried out a spontaneous unauthorised piece of performance art in [[Brook Green]], [[Hammersmith]]; during the performance, police arrived and put a stop to the event, deeming it obscene.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=4.18&ndash;4.21}}

In September 1974, COUM were invited to attend the [[Stadfest]] in [[Rottweil]], [[West Germany]], and they proceeded with a travel grant from the [[British Council]].{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.22}} There, they published two performance art actions in the street, earning them praise from [[Bridget Riley]] and [[Ernst Jandl]], both of whom were present.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=4.22&ndash;4.25}} The acclaim that COUM received at Rottweil established the group's reputation as "one of the most innovative performance art groups then on the London art scene", convincing the Arts Council and British Council to take them more seriously and offer them greater support.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.25}}

{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = right
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  = 
|title_fnt = 
|title     = 
|quote     = "COUM is not 'about' entertainment, it is coumcerned [sic] with direct, symbolic interpretation of actions to realise a uniquely personal perception."
|salign    = right
|source    = P-Orridge, 1974.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=4.13}} }}

In February 1975, P-Orridge gained his first full-time job, working as an assistant editor at [[St. James' Press]], in which he helped to compile the ''Contemporary Artists'' reference book. The work meant that he had less time to devote to COUM but gained a wide range of contacts in the art world.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.4}} During that year, COUM embarked on a series of five performance pieces which it termed ''Omissions''; these were performed across Europe.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=5.4, 5.6&ndash;5.7}} In March 1975, COUM performed ''Couming of Youth'' at the [[Melkweg]] in Amsterdam. Adopting a more violent stance than their previous work &ndash; in this reflecting an influence from the Viennese Actionists &ndash; the performance involved self-mutilation, Cosey inserting lighted candles into her vagina, P-Orridge being crucified and whipped, and P-Orridge and Cosey having sexual intercourse.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=5.7&ndash;5.9}} At [[Southampton]]'s [[Nuffield Festival]] in July 1975, COUM performed ''Studio of Lust'', where P-Orridge publicly masturbated and all of the members undressed and adopted sexual poses.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=5.10&ndash;5.11}}

===Establishing Throbbing Gristle and the Prostitution show: 1975&ndash;1976===

COUM were introduced to [[Chris Carter (British musician)|Chris Carter]] in the summer of 1975 through their mutual friend John Lacey. Lacey believed that Carter would be interested in COUM as a result of his particular interest in the experimental use of light and sound.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.15}} Together, Carter, Christopherson, Cosey and P-Orridge founded a musical band, Throbbing Gristle, on 3 September 1975; they had deliberately chosen that date for it was the 36th anniversary of the United Kingdom joining the [[Second World War]].{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.16}} The term "throbbing gristle" was deliberately chosen for it was a Yorkshire slang term for an erect penis.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.16}} Throbbing Gristle, or TG as it was widely known, was aimed at a wider audience than COUM, thereby aiming to work within [[popular culture]] rather than the elite realm of the art scene.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.17}} COUM and TG were largely treated as distinct entities; the music press ignored COUM and saw TG as experimental [[art rock]], while the arts press ignored TG, viewing COUM as performance artists.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.17}} Despite their intention of operating within the realms of popular culture, TG never had chart success, and remained a [[cult band]]; their audience was however far larger than COUM.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.18}}

{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = left
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  = 
|title_fnt = 
|title     = 
|quote     = "When we shifted from Coum Transmissions to TG, we were also stating that we wanted to go into ''popular culture'', away from the art gallery context, and show that the same technique that had been made to operate in that system could work. We wanted to test it out in the real world, or nearer to the real world, at a more street level &ndash; with young kids who had no education in art perception, who didn't come along and either empathised or didn't; either liked the noise or didn't. A little mini-Dada movement, eh?"
|salign    = right
|source    = P-Orridge, 1983.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=5.17&ndash;5.18}} }}

COUM continued to operate alongside TG, and in October 1975 they performed ''Jusquà la balle crystal'''' at the Ninth Paris Biennale at the Musée d'art modern. The prestige of being invited to such an event led to the Arts Council awarding them a grant for £1,600, although only the first half of this was ever paid out.{{sfn|Ford|1999|pp=5.19&ndash;5.21}} COUM's [[mail art]] had taken on an increasingly pornographic dimension, and in November 1975 the police charged P-Orridge with distributing obscene material via in the postal system under the [[1953 Post Office Act]]; this trial was set for February 1976.{{sfn|Ford|1999|p=5.21}}
They were prosecuted in 1975 for making collages combining postcards of Queen Elizabeth with soft-core porn, but the jail term and fines were suspended on condition they did not continue.<ref name="house">House D. (4 April 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20090421065829/http://www.rocknrolldating.com/interview/genesis-p.-orridge-pt.-i Genesis P-Orridge Interview, Part I] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20170327055811/http://www.rocknrolldating.com/interview/genesis-p.-orridge-pt.-ii Part II.] ''RocknRollDating''</ref>

Their ''Prostitution'' show, in 1976 at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]] (ICA) in London, included displays of Tutti's pornographic images from magazines as well as erotic nude photographs;<ref name=disinfo-150>[[#Metz02|Metzger 2002]] p. 150</ref> the show featured a stripper, used [[tampons]] in glass,<ref name=disinfo-150/> and [[transvestism|transvestite]] guards. Prostitutes, [[Punk subculture|punk]]s, and people in costumes were among those hired to mingle with the gallery audience. The show caused debate in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] about the public funding of such events. In the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], Scottish [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP Sir [[Nicholas Fairbairn]] demanded an explanation from Arts Minister [[Harold Lever]] and proclaimed P-Orridge and Tutti as "wreckers of civilisation".<ref name="williams">Williams, Sheldon.  "Genesis P-Orridge". pp.&nbsp;770–772 in Naylor, Colin & Genesis P-Orridge (editors).   ''Contemporary Artists''. Macmillan Press/St Martin's Press, 1977. {{ISBN|0-333-22672-0}}</ref> [[Fleet Street]] was not slow to pick up the story. The reviews were cut up, framed, and put on display for the remainder of the exhibition.<ref name=disinfo-150/> This was also reported in newspapers, so cut-ups about the cut-ups were also put on display.<ref name=disinfo-150/> COUM was found so offensive that it lost its government grant,<ref>{{cite book | author=Thompson, Dave | title=Alternative Rock | page=685 | publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-87930-607-6}}</ref> and went on to become the private company [[Industrial Records]].<ref name=devolution>{{cite book | author=Mulholland, Neil | title=The Cultural Devolution: Art in Britain in the Late Twentieth Century | page=158 | publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd | year=2003 | isbn=978-0-7546-0392-4}}</ref> Toward the end of COUM, performances would often consist of only P-Orridge, Cosey and Sleazy, the core group who went on to form [[Throbbing Gristle]].<ref>{{cite book | author1= Sladen, Mark | author2=Yedgar, Ariella | title=Panic Attack!: Art in the Punk Years | page=9 | publisher=Merrell | year=2007 | isbn=978-1-85894-403-6}}</ref>

==Throbbing Gristle==
{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = right
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  = 
|title_fnt = 
|title     = 
|quote     = "I've been involved in a total war with culture since the day I started&nbsp;... I am at war with the status quo of society and I am at war with those in control and power. I'm at war with hypocrisy and lies, I'm at war with the mass media. Then I'm at war with every bastard who tries to hurt someone else for its own sake. And I'm at war with privilege and I'm at war with all the things that one should be at war with basically. As my mentor used to say: "I feel your pain, I feel your shame but you're not to blame"."
|salign    = right
|source    = Genesis P-Orridge, 1989<ref>[[#Abe11|P-Orridge in Abrahamsson 2011 [1989]]]. p. 42.</ref>
}}
[[Throbbing Gristle]] was formed in the autumn of 1975<ref name=allmusictg>{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=p5651 | tab=biography | label=Throbbing Gristle Biography | first=Jason | last=Ankeny | accessdate=14 February 2012}}</ref> as a four-piece band, consisting of P-Orridge, [[Cosey Fanni Tutti]], [[Peter Christopherson|Peter "Sleazy" Christopherson]] and [[Chris Carter (British musician)|Chris Carter]].<ref name=allmusictg/>
The name "Throbbing Gristle" was adopted after a Northern English slang term for an erect penis.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=99}} P-Orridge's involvement in Throbbing Gristle led to the artist being regularly cited as the "Godfather of [[Industrial Music]]",{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=179}} or in some later sources, "godparent".<ref name="Reinventions"/>

The first Throbbing Gristle performance was held at the Air Gallery in London in July 1976.<ref name=devolution/> At that point, Throbbing Gristle's headquarters was located at 10 Martello Street, [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney, East London]], the address of an artist collective. P-Orridge and Tutti's living and work space was the mailing address of [[Industrial Records]] (IR). Throbbing Gristle released "[[Discipline (Throbbing Gristle song)|Discipline]]" in 1980.<ref>S. Alexander Reed, ''Assimilate: A Critical History of Industrial Music'' (2013, {{ISBN|0199832609}})</ref> TG came to be identified as the founders of [[industrial music]],{{sfn|Daniel|2008|p=2}} although at the same time the academic Drew Daniel asserted that as a result of its eclecticism, their music resists clear analysis.{{sfn|Daniel|2008|pp=1–2}}

Throbbing Gristle's best-selling single was "[[Zyklon B Zombie]]" (1978), the title being a reference to the [[Zyklon B]] poison gas used at [[Auschwitz extermination camp]].{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=208}} With their album ''[[20 Jazz Funk Greats]]'' they attempted to move away from their industrial sound, and produced songs in a variety of different musical genres.{{sfn|Daniel|2008|p=2}} P-Orridge received a number of threatening phone calls, proceeding to record them and use them as a backing track for the TG song "Death Threats".{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=100}}

The final IR release was called ''[[Nothing Here Now But the Recordings]]'', a best-of album taken from the archives of [[William S. Burroughs]], who provided P-Orridge and Christopherson with access to his reel-to-reel tape archive.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.com/?id=CIea5OniG30C&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Nothing+Here+but+the+Recordings%22#v=onepage&q=%22Nothing%20Here%20but%20the%20Recordings%22&f=false | author=Kansa, Spencer | title=William S. Burroughs: Rock God | work=Beatdown | issue=7 |date=July 2010}}</ref>

The final Throbbing Gristle live event, ''[[Mission of Dead Souls]]'', occurred in May 1981 at the [[Kezar Pavilion]] in San Francisco, US.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=4WM6Cb1z-PwC&pg=PA577&lpg=PA577&dq=Mission+of+Dead+Souls,+May+1981+San+Francisco#v=onepage&q=Mission%20of%20Dead%20Souls%2C%20May%201981%20San%20Francisco&f=false | author=Gimarc, George | title=Punk Diary: The Ultimate Trainspotter's Guide To Underground Rock, 1970–1982 | page=577 | publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation |date=July 2005 | isbn=9780879308483 }}</ref> Shortly after the San Francisco event, P-Orridge and [[Paula P-Orridge]] (née Alaura O'Dell) were married.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}

During this period, P-Orridge befriended an English musician named David Bunting; P-Orridge already knew another man named David, so coined the moniker [[David Tibet]],{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=210}} which Bunting adopted as a stage name. Through an introduction provided by Burroughs, P-Orridge met [[Brion Gysin]] in Paris, probably in 1980, coming to be deeply influenced by Gysin's [[Cut-up technique|cut-up method]]; P-Orridge understood this to be a revolutionary method of escaping current patterns of thought and developing something new.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|pp=198–199}}

==Psychic TV and Thee Temple Ov Psychic Youth==
[[File:Genesis P. Orridge.jpg|thumb|Genesis P-Orridge posing in Japan]]
{{main|Psychic TV|Thee Temple ov Psychick Youth}}
Following the break-up of Throbbing Gristle, in 1981 P-Orridge founded a band with [[Peter Christopherson]] and [[Alex Fergusson (musician)|Alex Fergusson]] that they named Psychic TV.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=202}} Involved in video art, they also performed psychedelic, punk, electronic and experimental music.<ref name=allmusicptv>{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=p5194 | tab=biography | label=Psychic TV Biography | first=Steve | last=Huey | accessdate=14 February 2012}}</ref> The decision to name the band "Psychic TV" stemmed from P-Orridge's belief that while mainstream television was a form of mass indoctrination and mind control, it could be used as an "esoterrorist" form of magick to combat the establishment's control.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=203}} Historian Dave Evans described Psychic TV as "a band dedicated to musical eclecticism and magical experiment, their performances being in part ritual (ab)use of sound samples, the creation of 'auditory magical sigils' and the destruction of consensus language in order to find meaning".{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=99}}

The band's first song, "Just Drifting", was based on a poem by P-Orridge.<ref name="porridge2002">P-Orridge, Genesis, Douglas Rushkoff (foreword), and Carl Abrahamsson (introduction). ''Painful but Fabulous: The Life and Art of Genesis P-Orridge''. Soft Skull Press, 2002. {{ISBN|1-887128-88-3}}</ref> For their first album, ''Force the Hand of Chance'' (1982), P-Orridge used a [[kangling]], or Tibetan trumpet made out of a human thigh-bone; the instrument had been introduced to P-Orridge by [[David Tibet]], and attracted attention to their music.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=203}} P-Orridge had become acquainted with [[Anton LaVey]], founder of the [[Church of Satan]] and ideologue of [[LaVeyan Satanism]],{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=158}} with LaVey making an appearance on the Psychic TV song "Joy", in which he recites the [[Lord's Prayer]] backwards.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=179}} From 1988, the band came under the increasing influence of the [[acid house]] genre of dance music,{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=179}} and were responsible for helping the popularisation of acid house music in Europe.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=156}}

Psychic TV made its debut in 1982 at an event organised by P-Orridge, David Dawson, and Roger Ely, called ''The Final Academy''. It was a 4-day multimedia celebratory rally held in Manchester and at the Ritzy Cinema in Brixton, South London. It brought performers and audience together with literature, performance, film and music. PTV, [[Cabaret Voltaire (band)|Cabaret Voltaire]], [[23 Skidoo (band)|23 Skidoo]], [[Z'EV]], [[John Giorno]], William S. Burroughs, [[Brion Gysin]], Terry Wilson, [[Jeff Nuttall]], and The Last Few Days participated to honour the cut-up techniques and theories of [[William S. Burroughs]], [[Ian Sommerville (technician)|Ian Sommerville]], [[Antony Balch]] and Gysin. Video projection and early [[Sampling (music)|sampling]] were used here, as well as whispered utterances by P-Orridge reprocessed as a soundtrack to Gysin's [[Dreamachine|Dreammachine]] by the [[Hafler Trio]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=pq_o5ky6MiYC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=genesis+p-orridge+hafler+trio+dreamachine#v=onepage&q=genesis%20p-orridge%20hafler%20trio%20dreamachine&f=false | author=Klarion | title=Dream On | work=Headpress 25 |date=October 2003 | publisher=Headpress| isbn=9781900486262 }}</ref> In the mid-eighties, Psychic TV aimed to release a live album on the 23rd of each month for 23 months<ref name=allmusicptv/> in recognition of [[the 23 enigma]]. The group didn't reach its goal but still managed fourteen albums in eighteen months, thus earning them an entry in the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]].<ref name=allmusicptv/> Following the culmination of Psychic TV but before embarking on Thee Majesty, P-Orridge and several Psychic TV musicians formed Splinter Test, a name adopted from one of P-Orridge's essays on sampling.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=201}}

In 1981,{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=156}} P-Orridge also founded a loosely organised network of occultists named [[Thee Temple ov Psychick Youth]] (TOPY), with the aid of Balance, Tibet, and a number of members of the [[Process Church of the Final Judgement]], a group which had exerted an influence on P-Orridge's occult thought.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=202}}<ref>{{cite book | author=Greer, John Michael | title=The New Encyclopedia of the Occult | page=474 | publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide | year=2003 | isbn=978-1-56718-336-8}}</ref> TOPY was conceived not as an occult order of teaching, but a forum to facilitate discussions on occult ideas by like-minded people, and from its beginnings was understood by its founders to be a successor to the late 19th and early 20th century [[Ordo Templi Orientis]] (OTO), especially as the latter had been run under Crowley's leadership.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=204}} Evans described TOPY as "a 'fusion' organisation, creating a crossover of punk/experimental music with [[chaos magic]]al thinking and practice", making particular use of the sigilisation practices of occult artist [[Austin Osman Spare]].{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=358}} Journalist Gavin Baddeley described TOPY as "perhaps the most influential new occult order of the 1980s".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=156}} P-Orridge had never wanted to be seen as the leader of an occult order, although many of those involved in TOPY were frustrated that outsiders regularly described P-Orridge as the group's leader. Accordingly, P-Orridge separated from TOPY in 1991, although it continued as a fan community after the departure.{{sfnm|1a1=Evans|1y=2007|1p=358|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=157|3a1=Partridge|3y=2013|3p=202}}

{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = left
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  = 
|title_fnt = 
|title     = 
|quote     = "We realized that the best response to that was just to go over to America and very quietly prove that that wasn’t what we were like. Just let people learn by themselves that we were intelligent, articulate, thoughtful, loving people. And that, in the end, that would deflate everything else. And it did."
|salign    = right
|source    = P-Orridge, on the move to New York City, 2016.<ref name="Reinventions"/>
}}

Having been encouraged by Christian groups involved in propagating the [[moral panic]] about alleged [[Satanic ritual abuse]],{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=157}} the [[Channel 4]] 1992 documentary show ''[[Dispatches (TV series)|Dispatches]]'' claimed to have discovered videotapes depicting P-Orridge sexually abusing children in a ritual setting.{{sfn|Evans|2007|pp=100–101}} Police from the [[Obscene Publications Squad]] subsequently raided P-Orridge's home, and confiscated several tonnes of art work.{{sfnm|1a1=Evans|1y=2007|1p=101|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=157}} At the time, P-Orridge was in Thailand undertaking famine-relief work; fearing arrest and loss of child custody upon return to the UK, P-Orridge stayed out of the country for several years, settling in the United States.{{sfnm|1a1=Evans|1y=2007|1p=101|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=157}} P-Orridge believed that the negative press and police attention were the result of a vendetta conceived by a right-wing fundamentalist Christian group.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=101}} It was subsequently revealed that the footage obtained did not depict child abuse. Instead, it was a video artwork titled ''First Transmissions'' that had been made in the early 1980s, partially funded by Channel 4 themselves; the footage depicted [[Sex magic|sex-magic]] rites between adults, blood-letting performances, and scenes of the filmmaker [[Derek Jarman]] reading passages from the work of [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]. Embarrassed by these revelations, Channel 4 retracted their initial accusations.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=101}}

==Later life==

===1993–2009: The Pandrogeny Project===
{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = right
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  =
|title_fnt =
|title     =
|quote     = "[W]e arrived [in Ridgewood] as husband and wife, me still dressing and technically behaving male, and all the local shopkeepers who knew Jaye from being a kid, all the neighbors&nbsp;... And then over the years, we transformed more and more until we were both running around in miniskirts, dressed the same, and none of them said anything! Except in the pharmacy, where very politely, one of the Pakistani guys we knew very well there&nbsp;... he says one day, "Hope you don't mind me asking, but you probably want us to say 'Miss P-Orridge' now, don't you?" We said, "That would be good!" And that was the one time anyone even mentioned that anything had happened."
|salign    = right
|source    = Genesis P-Orridge, 2011<ref name="Cam"/>
}}

In January 1993, Genesis and second wife to-be, Lady Jaye (née Jacqueline Breyer), moved to [[Ridgewood, Queens|Ridgewood]], Queens in New York City.<ref name="Cam">{{cite news|title=Artist Provocateur Genesis Breyer P-Orridge Lives By the Last Exit To Brooklyn|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2011-02-16/news/genesis-p-orridge-throbbing-gristle-home-manhattan/|accessdate=30 January 2013|newspaper=The Village Voice|date=16 February 2011|author=Camille Dodero|agency=Village Voice, LLC}}</ref>  Here they embarked on the "Pandrogeny Project"; influenced by the cut-up technique, the duo underwent body modification to resemble one another, thus coming to identify themselves as a single pandrogynous being named "Breyer P-Orridge".{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=200}}<ref name="Doorne">{{cite web|title=Genesis P Orridge|url=http://www.bizarremag.com/entertainment/heroes/6441/genesis_p_orridge.html|work=Bizarre|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing Limited]]|accessdate=30 January 2013|last=Doorne|first=James|others=Photos: Neville Elder; Breyer P. Orridge |date=January 2008}}</ref>  In doing so, the pair spent $200,000 on surgical alteration, receiving breast implants, cheek and chin implants, lip plumping, eye and nose jobs, tattooing, and hormone therapy, while also adopting gender neutral and alternating pronouns.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=200}}<ref name="orden"/><ref name="Oursler">{{cite web|title=Tony Oursler (b. 1957)|url=http://ubu.com/film/oursler_p-orridge.html|work=UbuWeb Film|publisher=UbuWeb|accessdate=30 January 2013|author=Tony Oursler|year=1997–2001}}</ref>  With this project, P-Orridge's intent was to express a belief that the self is pure consciousness trapped within the DNA-governed body.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=200}}  The couple adopted the term "pandrogyne" because – in their words – "we wanted a word without any history or any connections with things – a word with its own story and its own information".<ref>{{cite news|title=Genesis P-Orridge on Pandrogyny and Surgery |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2012-03-07/columns/Michael-Musto-Genesis-Lady-Jaye/full/ |accessdate=30 January 2013 |newspaper=The Village Voice |date=7 March 2012 |author=Michael Musto |agency=Village Voice, LLC |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235055/http://www.villagevoice.com/2012-03-07/columns/Michael-Musto-Genesis-Lady-Jaye/full/ |archivedate=2 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>
He also stated that:

{{quote|We started out, because we were so crazy in love, just wanting to eat each other up, to become each other and become one. And as we did that, we started to see that it was affecting us in ways that we didn't expect. Really, we were just two parts of one whole; the pandrogyne was the whole and we were each other's other half.<ref name="Suicidebody">{{cite web|title=Genesis P-Orridge: The Body Politic|url=http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Genesis+P-Orridge%3A+The+Body+Politic/|work=Suicide Girls|publisher=SuicideGirls|accessdate=30 January 2013|author=Tamara Palmer|date=29 December 2008}}</ref> }}

During this era, a book was published of Breyer P-Orridge's writings, poems, and observations, called ''Ooh, You Are Awful&nbsp;... But I Like You!''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cut Ups: The post-gender Genesis Breyer P-Orridge's Psychic TV lands at Reggies Rock Club|url=http://music.newcity.com/2011/12/07/cut-ups-the-post-gender-genesis-breyer-p-orridges-psychic-tv-lands-at-reggies-rock-club/|work=Newcity Music|publisher=Newcity Communications, Inc|accessdate=30 January 2013|author=Arvo Zylo|date=7 December 2011}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Breyer P-Orridge collaborated with different people in music, including [[Pigface]], [[Skinny Puppy]], and [[Download (band)|Download]]. Breyer P-Orridge also performed with [[Nik Turner]] and other former members of [[Hawkwind]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nik Turner's Space Ritual 1994 video review|url=http://www.starfarer.net/nik94vhs.html|work=Starfarer's Hawkwind Page|publisher=Starfarer|accessdate=30 January 2013|author=Starfarer|date=6 October 2004|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117061308/http://www.starfarer.net/nik94vhs.html|archivedate=17 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[File:Psychictv-cologne-2004.jpg|thumb|left|PTV3 live in Germany 2004: Alice Genese, G. P-Orridge, Markus Persson]]
In June 1998, Breyer P-Orridge won a $1.5&nbsp;million lawsuit against producer [[Rick Rubin]] and his [[American Recordings (US)|American Recordings]] label for injuries sustained while trying to escape a fire at Rubin's home in April 1995.<ref name="LLC2006">{{cite book|author=SPIN Media LLC|title=SPIN|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BvUVT5TnUCwC&pg=PT9|accessdate=30 January 2013|date=May 2006|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|pages=9–|issn=0886-3032}}</ref> According to Breyer P-Orridge's attorney, David D. Stein, Breyer P-Orridge was staying at Rubin's home, as a guest of [[Love and Rockets (band)|Love and Rockets]], when the fire broke out. Breyer P-Orridge tried to escape the house by crawling through a second-story window and fell onto concrete stairs. Between them, Breyer P-Orridge suffered a broken wrist, broken ribs, and a [[pulmonary embolism]], as well as a shattered left elbow that, according to Stein, has prevented P-Orridge from playing bass or keyboards. They remained in hospital for a total of ten days.<ref name="LLC2006" /> The jury found that the liability for the fire rested with Rubin and American Recordings, and awarded Breyer P-Orridge [[United States dollar|US$]]1,572,000 in compensation.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425395/psychic-tv-founder-awarded-damages-against-rick-rubin-american-recordings.jhtml | author= | title=Psychic TV Founder Awarded Damages Against Rick Rubin, American Recordings | work=[[MTV]].com | publisher=[[Viacom]] | date=17 June 1998 | accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref>

In 1999, Breyer P-Orridge performed with the briefly reunited late-1980s version of Psychic TV for an event at London's [[Royal Festival Hall]], called ''Time's Up''.  The MC for the event, via pre-recorded video, was [[Quentin Crisp]], it was recorded and [[Time's Up Live|released as a DVD]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/260728/Psychic-TV-Time-s-Up-Live/overview | title=Psychic TV: Time's Up Live (1999) | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref> ''[[Time's Up (Thee Majesty album)|Time's Up]]'' is also the title of the first CD by [[Thee Majesty]], Breyer P-Orridge's spoken-word project with "noise" guitarist, Bryin Dall.

In December 2003, Breyer P-Orridge, using the alias ''Djinn'', unveiled PTV3, a new act drawing upon the early "Hyperdelic" work of Psychic TV with media theorist [[Douglas Rushkoff]] among its members.<ref name="gilbert">{{cite web|title=Genesis Breyer P-Orridge: an interview |url=http://www.soundsect.com/feature.php?id=9 |work=soundsect.com |publisher=soundsect.com |accessdate=30 January 2013 |author=Tom Gilbert |date=31 August 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208100527/http://www.soundsect.com/feature.php?id=9 |archivedate=8 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 16 May 2004 all four former members of Throbbing Gristle performed at the [[London Astoria]] for the first time in 23 years.

Breyer P-Orridge appeared in the 1998 film and 2000 book versions of ''[[Modulations A History of Electronic Music|Modulations]]'', in the 1999 film [[Better Living Through Circuitry]], in the 2004 film ''[[DiG!]]'', the 2006 documentary [[Monks: The Transatlantic Feedback]], in Nik Sheehan's 2007 feature documentary on the [[Dreamachine]] entitled 'FLicKeR', and the 2010 documentary "[[William S. Burroughs: A Man Within]]".{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}

In January 2006, the new PTV album was announced on P-Orridge's website. ''[[Hell Is Invisible... Heaven Is Her/e]]'' was recorded in NYC and features [[Nick Zinner]] ([[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]]) and [[Gibby Haynes]] ([[Butthole Surfers]]) guesting on some tracks.  To inaugurate the release of ''Hell Is Invisible&nbsp;... Heaven Is Her/e'', PTV3 hosted a five night residency in September 2006 at Galapagos Art Space in [[Brooklyn|Williamsburg, Brooklyn]], New York.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.smarttix.com/show.aspx?showCode=PSY2 | title=Galapagos Art Space Presents Psychic TV | accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref> ''[[Mr. Alien Brain Vs. the Skinwalkers]]'' was released on Sweet Nothing Records on 8 December 2008.<ref name="orden">{{cite web|title=I Am My Own Wife |url=http://nymag.com/arts/art/profiles/58864/ |website=New York Magazine |accessdate=30 January 2013 |first=Erica |last=Orden |date=6 September 2009 |dead-url=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170620/http://nymag.com/arts/art/profiles/58864/ |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mr-alien-brain-vs-the-skinwalkers-mw0000804604 | title=Mr. Alien Brain Vs. the Skinwalkers Overview | publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] | accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Genesis p orridge 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Genesis P-Orridge in 2007]]

On 9 October 2007, Lady Jaye Breyer P-Orridge died.<ref name="visco">{{cite news | url=http://nypress.com/s-he-is-still-her-e-memorial-for-lady-jaye-breyer-p-orridge/ | author=Visco, Gerry | title=S/hE Is (Still) Her/e: Memorial for Lady Jaye Breyer P-Orridge | work=[[New York Press]] | date=8 March 2008 | accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref> The cause of death was a heart condition that was possibly related to stomach cancer. Psychic TV cancelled its North American tour dates in the aftermath of Lady Jaye's death. A memorial was held at the Participant Inc. Gallery in New York City on 8 March 2008 .<ref>{{cite web|title=Genesis P. Orridge announces Lady Jaye Memorial 3/8|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/archives/2008/02/genesis_p_orrid.html|work=Brooklyn Vegan|publisher=Brooklyn Vegan|accessdate=30 January 2013|date=19 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Jaye Memorial by Genesis Breyer P-Orridge|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/gerryvisco/sets/72157604086627593/|work=flickr|publisher=Yahoo! Inc|accessdate=30 January 2013|author=Genesis Breyer P-Orridge|format=Photo upload|date=8 March 2008}}</ref> As of January 2013, P-Orridge's official website says, "Since that time Genesis continues to represent the amalgam Breyer P-Orridge in the material 'world' and Lady Jaye represents the amalgam Breyer P-Orridge in the immaterial 'world' creating an ongoing interdimensional collaboration."<ref name=homepage/> Thus, P-Orridge continued the Pandrogyne Project, having further surgical operations to alter their body and using "we" when in reference to themselves; however, to a reporter P-Orridge admitted that without Lady Jaye, "It's very hard. The bottom line is that we know she would continue. She wouldn't stop because it was complicated."<ref name="orden"/> From this point, P-Orridge began referring to themselves in the plural in order to keep Breyer's memory alive.<ref name="Reinventions"/>

===2009–present: Retirement from touring===
In September 2009, a retrospective of P-Orridge's collages, entitled "30 Years of Being Cut Up", opened at [[Invisible-Exports]].<ref name="orden"/>
On 4 November 2009 it was announced that P-Orridge would retire from touring in any and all bands (including Throbbing Gristle and Psychic TV) to concentrate on art, writing and music.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}

In June 2010, P-Orridge sold the Ridgewood property, holding a [[garage sale]] in the basement of a local art gallery to sell off a range of personal items, in addition to an array of [[dildo]]s.<ref name="Cam" /> This accomplished, P-Orridge moved to a one-bedroom apartment in New York's [[Lower East Side]],<ref name="Cam" /> and continued producing art in this home.<ref name="Reinventions"/> P-Orridge returned to touring with Psychic TV in 2016 with the release of their album ''[[Alienist (album)|Alienist]]''. The tour lasted from mid-September to early December, with concerts in Greece, Israel, Poland, Russia, Ukraine, the United Kingdom and the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 August 2016 |title=Psychic TV "Alienist" Fall Tour Dates Announced! |website=P-Orridge Shoppe |url=https://porridgeshoppe.myshopify.com/blogs/frontpage/psychic-tv-alienist-fall-tour-dates-announced|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref>

In August 2015, P-Orridge gained publicity for an interview critical of [[Caitlyn Jenner]]'s self-description as a "spokesperson" for the transgender community, stating that Jenner was "clueless" and did not know what life was like for the majority of transgender people around the world.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 August 2016 |title=Genesis P-Orridge: Caitlyn Jenner should 'stop being a spokesperson' |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/aug/27/genesis-p-orridge-caitlyn-jenner-transgender-spokesperson |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>
In the summer of 2016, P-Orridge's artwork was the subject of an exhibition, "Try to Altar Everything", at the [[Rubin Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]]. The exhibition contained paintings, sculptures, and installations inspired by the [[Hindu mythology]] that P-Orridge had encountered in Kathmandu.<ref name="Battaglia">{{cite web |last=Battaglia |first=Andy |date=1 July 2016 |title=Could it be magick? The occult returns to the art world  |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/01/magick-occult-returns-art-world-genesis-breyer-p-orridge |accessdate=2 July 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702185603/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/01/magick-occult-returns-art-world-genesis-breyer-p-orridge |archivedate=2 July 2016 |dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="Reinventions">{{cite web |last=Hoby |first=Hermione |date=29 June 2016 |title=The Reinventions of Genesis P-Orridge |website=The New Yorker |url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-reinventions-of-genesis-breyer-p-orridge |access-date=2 July 2016 |archivedate=30 June 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630161757/http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-reinventions-of-genesis-breyer-p-orridge |dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kennedy |first=Randy |date=2 March 2016 |title=Genesis Breyer P-Orridge, a Shape-Shifter, Pays Homage to Hindu Myths |website=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/arts/design/genesis-breyer-p-orridge-a-shape-shifter-pays-homage-to-hindu-myths.html?_r=0 |accessdate=2 July 2016 }}</ref> In June 2016, P-Orridge featured as a model in a campaign by the designer [[Marc Jacobs]], who described P-Orridge as "a sort of come-to-life definition of realness and authenticity".<ref name="Reinventions"/>

==Work==
{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = right
|fontsize  = 85%
|title_bg  = 
|title_fnt = 
|title     = 
|quote     = "Fusing esoteric ideas with the subversive methods of people like Burroughs and Gysin, P-Orridge and other musicians explored taboo areas and forbidden knowledge in an attempt to create a free-thinking occult culture in which individuals were the resources with which they might be able to carve out their own future[...] What they tried to do with music was wreck the civilization that had rejected and oppressed them. This was occultural direct action – esoterrorism!"
|salign    = right
|source    = Christopher Partridge, 2013.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=206}}
}}
Influenced by concepts from both [[Western esotericism]] and [[Modern paganism|contemporary Paganism]], P-Orridge's work is designed to confront the audience with ways of thinking alien to the mainstream values of Western society.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=190}} The [[religious studies]] scholar [[Christopher Partridge]] characterised P-Orridge's work as being a "confluence of pornography, violence, death, degradation, the confrontation of taboo subjects, noise and Paganism", deliberately courting controversy and expressing an anti-establishment stance.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|pp=189–190}} Partridge suggested that this intent to shock emerged both out of a serious attempt to highlight the mechanisms of [[social control]] in Western society and also out of "a juvenile delight gained from extreme behaviour and the offence caused".{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=190}}

P-Orridge's work was particularly influenced by the early 20th-century English artist and occultist [[Austin Osman Spare]], who shared his disdain for mainstream morality and fascination with sexuality and the human body.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=195}} P-Orridge adopted Spare's views on [[Sigil (magic)|sigils]], coming to see their own work as a form of sigil magic.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|pp=196–197}} Spare's sigilisation process entailed writing down one's desires, before crossing out any letters that are repeated and then combining the remaining letters into an abstract design, or sigil; the magician must then focus on that sigil and mentally absorb it, and – according to Spare's claims – psychic energies operating on the subconscious ensure that the original desire is manifested in reality. P-Orridge adopted this theory, believing that their work operates according to its principles.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|pp=196–197}}

A further element of P-Orridge's work is their common use of idiosyncratically use of grammar and spelling, such as "Thee" in place of "the", "ov" in place of "of" and (especially in early writings) "butter" in place of "but". The purpose of this is to challenge thought and established ways of reading.{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=201}}

==Personal life==
{{Quote box
|width     = 30em
|border    = 1px
|align     = right
|fontsize  = 85%
|quote     = "I'm 38 and for all my faults I have spent most of those 38 years searching determinedly for ideas that work and ideas that help. Not everyone maybe, but some people. If they work and if they make any kind of sense, the only way to check is to give them to other people and see if it works. If it helps one or two or ten or fifteen, that's a massive improvement on what most human beings do in their life to help anyone. If it helps a few hundred or a few thousand, that's incredible."
|salign    = right
|source    = Genesis P-Orridge, 1989.<ref name="P-Orridge 2011 37">[[#Abe11|P-Orridge in Abrahamsson 2011 [1989]]]. p. 37.</ref>
}}
P-Orridge has two daughters, Caresse and Genesse, with former wife [[Paula P-Orridge]] (born Paula Brooking). An interview with Genesis and Paula P-Orridge appeared in the book ''[[Modern Primitives (book)|RE/Search: Modern Primitives]]'' in 1989,<ref name="Modern Primitives">{{cite book |title=Modern Primitives |author1-link=V. Vale|last1=Vale|first1=V. |author2-link=Andrea Juno|last2=Juno|first2=Andrea |publisher=[[RE/Search]] |date=1989 |isbn=978-0-940642-14-0 |oclc=20973712}}</ref> and the Icelandic publication ''Eintak'' in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=# 65: Psychic TV in Iceland|url=http://icelandicmusicmuseum.blogspot.de/2012/01/65-psychic-tv-in-iceland.html|work=Icelandic Music Museum|publisher=Wim Van Hooste|accessdate=30 December 2013|author=Wim Van Hooste|date=21 January 2012}}</ref>

On a religious or spiritual level, Christopher Partridge described P-Orridge as representing "a particularly interesting, influential and subversive example of contemporary Paganism."{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=190}} Asserting that P-Orridge's "Industrial Paganism" was different from most forms of contemporary Paganism, Partridge described it as "confrontational, subversive, experimental and, to a large extent, dystopian", with it serving as "an ideological tool" with which to analyse society "from its underbelly; an immersion in the dark side; the subversion of Christian hegemony, conservative politics and what nowadays might be described as [[neoliberalism]]".{{sfn|Partridge|2013|pp=192–193}}
P-Orridge is devoted to the deity [[Eshu|Eshu Elegguá]], an entity from the Afro-Caribbean syncretic religion of [[Santería]].{{sfn|Partridge|2013|p=189}} However, P-Orridge has also stated a disbelief in the literal existence of [[Deity|gods]], deeming such entities to instead be "early attempts at psychology, trying to understand the light and dark side of human nature".<ref name="P-Orridge 2011 37"/>

P-Orridge has vociferously criticized contemporary Christianity, describing it as "an incredibly sick social pseudo-religion", and arguing that it was based upon the tenet of "Be good now, agree, or else we will punish you forever and ever when you're dead. And we may punish you while you're alive&nbsp;..."<ref name="P-Orridge 2011 37"/>  P-Orridge maintains that such an attitude was established in Christianity by [[St. Paul]] and the early Roman Catholic Church, and that it differed from the "ecstatic mysticism of the original Christianity, the [[Christian Gnosticism|Gnostic Christianity]]".<ref name="P-Orridge 2011 37"/>

P-Orridge was diagnosed with [[chronic myelomonocytic leukemia]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farley|first1=Donovan|title=Throbbing Gristle & Psychic TV founder Genesis Breyer P-Orridge announces leukemia diagnosis|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/10/throbbing-gristle-psychic-tv-founder-genesis-breyer-p-orridge-announces-leukemia-diagnosis/|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> As a consequence their scheduled appearance at the [[Hobart]]/[[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]] Mofo Festival, 20–21 Jan 2018, (with Edley O'Dowd), was cancelled.

==Reception and legacy==

According to ''New York'' magazine, P-Orridge became "an icon of the London avant-garde" in 1976.<ref name="orden"/>
Writing for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 2016, the reporter Hermione Hoby described P-Orridge as a "cult figure"<ref name="Reinventions"/> considered to be "a treasure of the avant-garde by global art institutions".<ref name="Reinventions"/>

