'''Victor Biaka Boda''' (February 25, 1913 – January 28, 1950) was an [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]] politician. Originally a [[shaman]], he adopted the name Victor and ventured into politics as a member of the [[Democratic Party of Côte d'Ivoire - African Democratic Rally]], and in 1948 was elected to the [[Senate of France|French Senate]].
He is best known for the unusual circumstances of his death. His death took place at the end of a [[Rassemblement Démocratique Africain#Chaos in the Ivory Coast: 1949|year of severe repression]] of his political party in the colony. In January 1950, while touring [[Bouaflé]], his car broke down. As his chauffeur repaired it, he strolled off into the jungle, never to return. His charred bones were recovered the following November. [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] reported in July 1951 that the most popular belief among French politicians was that "the Senator had been eaten by his constituents."<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,889084,00.html#ixzz1BXU8TGwC "FRANCE: Tabled?"], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 1951-07-16.</ref>
''Stade Victor Biaka Boda'', a stadium in [[Gagnoa]], is named in his honor.
